Configure Nexus with Jenkins Server
1. Create Docker Daemon Configuration
Create or edit the Docker daemon configuration file: Command: 
sudo nano /etc/docker/daemon.json 
Add the following content: 
{ "insecure-registries": ["136.113.46.39:8088"] } 
Save and exit (Ctrl + O, Enter, Ctrl + X).
2. Add Jenkins User to Docker Group
Allow the current user (or Jenkins user) to run Docker commands: 
sudo usermod -aG docker $USER 
Apply the new group membership without logging out: 
newgrp docker
3. Restart Docker Service
Restart the Docker daemon to apply the new configuration: sudo systemctl restart docker
4. Verify Insecure Registry Configuration
Check if the insecure registry is listed correctly: docker info | grep -A3 "Insecure
Registries"
5. Test Nexus Connectivity
Try logging in to your Nexus Docker registry: docker login 136.113.46.39:8088 -u admin
-p <password> If login succeeds, the Nexus Docker registry is successfully configured for your
Jenkins server.
